implementation:

  server.c — new additions before handle_root:
  - Includes: <ctype.h>, <fcntl.h>, <pthread.h>, <security/pam_appl.h>, <security/pam_misc.h>, <stdint.h>
  - Constants: SESSION_DIR, SESSION_ID_BYTES, SESSION_EXPIRY_SEC
  - generate_session_id() — reads 32 bytes from /dev/urandom, hex-encodes to 64-char ID
  - pam_conv_func() + authenticate_pam() — per-call PAM authentication, fully thread-safe
  - create_session() — atomic O_CREAT|O_EXCL file creation with 600 perms
  - parse_session_cookie() — extracts session=<id> from Cookie header
  - validate_session() — hex-validates ID (prevents path traversal), checks expiry
  - require_auth() — reusable middleware for protecting routes (returns -1 and sends 401 on failure)
  - handle_login() — POST /login handler
  - main() — mkdir(SESSION_DIR, 0700) at startup + CHTTP_POST(&srv, "/login", handle_login)

  run — added grep -q "pam_appl.h" "$SRC" && EXTRA_FLAGS="$EXTRA_FLAGS -lpam" for auto-detection.

  Note: PAM "login" service typically requires root. For dev/testing, create /etc/pam.d/chttp with a permissive config, then change pam_start("login", ...) to
  pam_start("chttp", ...).

